Google Play Store Analysis¶

BA-770-B/Team-7 Members:Kunpeng Huang, Haolan Ma, Yihan Jiang, Chengyu Liang, Meiling Zhang

The dataset we will be using is Google Play Store. In our project, we are going to analyze the popularity of applications in the Google Play Store. We defined popularity of an app as the number of installation. The larger the installation number means the app is more popular. We are going to use rating, price, review, size, genre, last updated version of the app and the latest updated time of the app as our independent variables. Furthermore, in order to gain insights of the Android applications market, we are supposed to determine what variables would have the most influential impact on the installation number (popularity) of the apps in Google Play Store and forecast the popularity of applications based on those significant variables.

Data Cleaning¶

In the following section, we are going to clean our data first since there are many missing variables and duplicated Apps in it.

Step 1¶

Rating represents the rating of the app in Google Play Store. In this step, we created a new table that includes App column and Rating column from the original table. There are duplicated App names in the original dataset. Since there are different rating for the same app, we chose the highest rating for each distinct app. We also have a condition specifying the Rating greater than or equal to 0 since there are NA values in Rating as well.

In [59]:
%%bq query
create or replace table `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_rating`
as
select app, max(rating) as rating_clean
From `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.googleplay` 
group by app
having rating_clean >=0

Step 2¶

Size represents the size of the App. The Size data in the original table have different units, some are in MB and the others are in KB. In addition, the data type of Size is String and we need to convert them into Float. In order to convert them into the same units, we firstly remove the "M" and then convert them into float and multiply them by 1024 for keeping them in KB. For the ones that are in KB, we simply remove the "k" and convert them into float.

In [1]:
%%bq query
create or replace table `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_size`
as
select app,
   cast(RTRIM(size,'M') as float64) *1024 as size_in_kb
 
  from  `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.googleplay` 
  where size like '%M'
  
union all 
(select app,cast(rtrim(size,'k') as float64)
from `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.googleplay` 
  where size like '%k')

Step 4¶

Installs represents the number of installation of each App. In the original dataset, Installs are Strings. In order to convert them into Integers, we firstly need to remove the "+" and "," in them. Then we used CAST() to convert them into Integers.

In [65]:
%%bq query
CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_installs`
AS
SELECT App, avg(CAST(installs_nocomma AS INT64)) as installs_clean FROM
(SELECT App, REPLACE (installs_noplus, ',' , '') AS installs_nocomma
 FROM
(SELECT App, REPLACE(Installs, '+' , '') AS installs_noplus
FROM `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.googleplay`))
group by app

Step 5¶

Last but not least, we created a small table that contains the variables that do not need cleaning, including price and category. (Type indicate the whether the app is free or not).
Again, since there are duplicated Apps in the dataset, we need to group by the apps, and in order to keep Price aggregated, we simply use the function AVG(). It will return the same number since the price is the same for the same app.

In [7]:
%%bq query
create or replace table `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_others`
as
select app,avg(price)as price,category,type, max(reviews) as max_review
from `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.googleplay`
group by app, category, type

Step 6¶

In this step, we put all the small tables together to form a large table that inclueds all the cleaned data and variables we would need in our furthur analysis by using INNER JOIN.

In [8]:
%%bq query
create or replace table `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.total`
as
select re.app, o.category, o.price,o.type,re.review_clean, ra.rating_clean, i.installs_clean,s.size_in_kb
from `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_review`as re
inner join`team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_others` as o
on re.app = o.app and re.review_clean=o.max_review
inner join `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_rating` as ra
on re.app = ra.app
inner join `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_installs` as i
on re.app= i.app
inner join `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.temp_size`as s
on re.app = s.app
order by app

Descriptive Data Analysis¶

Now, we are going to look at the relationship between installation and other variables.

Installation Distribution Before we look into the relationship between installation and other variables, we first looked at the frequency distribution of installation itself first. Firstly, we are showing the different range of applications' installtion in the Google Play Store. In the installation category, 50 means 50+, 1,000 means 1000+,etc. Secondlly, we set different bin values, in order to evluate installation performance in the Google Play Story. In this case, total 1419 different applications are installed from 100,000 to 1,000,000 times, which is the most frequency range.

In [1]:
%%bq query

In [9]:
%%bq query -n Installation_distribution 
Select 
   Case When installs_clean > 0 AND installs_clean <= 100 then '1-100'
    When installs_clean > 100 AND installs_clean <= 500 then '100-500'
      when installs_clean > 500 AND installs_clean <= 1000 then '500-1000'
        when installs_clean > 1000 AND installs_clean <= 5000 then '1000-5000'
          when installs_clean > 5000 AND installs_clean <= 10000 then '5000-10000'
           when installs_clean > 10000 AND installs_clean <= 100000 then '10000-100000'
            when installs_clean > 100000 AND installs_clean <= 500000 then '100000-500000'
              when installs_clean > 500000 AND installs_clean <= 1000000 then '500000-1000000'
                when installs_clean > 1000000 AND installs_clean <= 30000000 then '1000000-3000000'
                 when installs_clean > 3000000 AND installs_clean <= 50000000 then '1000000-3000000'
          else '50000000+' END AS Ranged, 
    Case when installs_clean > 0 AND installs_clean <= 100  then 1
    when installs_clean > 100 AND installs_clean <= 500 then 2
      When installs_clean > 500 AND installs_clean <= 1000 then 3
        when installs_clean > 1000 AND installs_clean <= 5000 then 4
          when installs_clean > 5000 AND installs_clean <= 10000  then 5
            when  installs_clean > 10000 AND installs_clean <= 100000 then 6
             when installs_clean > 100000 AND installs_clean <= 500000 then 7
                when installs_clean > 500000 AND installs_clean <= 1000000 then 8
                  when installs_clean > 1000000 AND installs_clean <= 30000000 then 9
                    when installs_clean > 3000000 AND installs_clean <= 50000000 then 10
                
          ELSE 11 END AS groupd, 
count(round(installs_clean, 0)) as  Numbers_of_installed_Application
From `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.total_distinct`
group by ranged, groupd
order by groupd

Size To explore the size variable, we first look at the distribution of sizes. We seperated them into different interveals from 0MB to 90MB and above by 10.
We can see from the bar chart that most of the sizes are below 1MB. The numbers of app decrease as the size of the app increase.The last bar shows the number of applications with size above 90MB.

In [1]:
%%bq query -n sizedis
Select 
    Case when size_in_kb > 0 AND size_in_kb <= 10*1024  then 0
    when size_in_kb > 10*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 20*1024 then 10
      When size_in_kb > 20*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 30*1024 then 20
        when size_in_kb > 30*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 40*1024 then 30
          when size_in_kb > 40*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 50*1024  then 40
            when  size_in_kb > 50*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 60*1024 then 50
             when size_in_kb > 60*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 70*1024 then 60
                when size_in_kb > 70*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 80*1024 then 70
                  when size_in_kb > 80*1024 AND size_in_kb <= 90*1024 then 80
                
          ELSE 90 END AS groupd, 
count(size_in_kb) as frequency 
From `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.total_distinct`
group by groupd
order by groupd

Classification Model¶

To build a binary classification model, we put apps into two categories, popular and unpopular. Popular apps have install amount >= 100000, unpopular apps have install amount < 100000.
We randomly select half of our data to train the model. It would classify apps "1" for popular, and "0" for unpopular.

In [28]:
%%bq query
CREATE or REPLACE MODEL googleplayapps.install_classmodel
OPTIONS
  (model_type='logistic_reg', labels=['popular_or_not']) AS

WITH params AS (
    SELECT
    0 AS TRAIN,
    1 AS EVAL
    ),
    
  appinfo AS (
  SELECT
    category,
    price,
    review_clean as review,
    rating_clean as rating,
    size_in_kb as size,
    case when installs_clean<100000 then 0
    else 1 end as popular_or_not
  FROM
    `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.total_distinct`, params
  WHERE
     MOD(ABS(FARM_FINGERPRINT(app)),2) = params.TRAIN
  )

  SELECT *
  FROM appinfo
Out[28]:
Done

Then we evaluate the model performance by AUC.

In [29]:
%%bq query
SELECT
  roc_auc,
  CASE
    WHEN roc_auc > .9 THEN 'good'
    WHEN roc_auc > .8 THEN 'fair'
    WHEN roc_auc > .7 THEN 'decent'
    WHEN roc_auc > .6 THEN 'not great'
  ELSE 'poor' END AS model_quality
FROM
  ML.EVALUATE(MODEL googleplayapps.install_classmodel,  (

WITH params AS (
    SELECT
    0 AS TRAIN,
    1 AS EVAL
    ),
    
  appinfo AS (
  SELECT
    category,
    price,
    review_clean as review,
    rating_clean as rating,
    size_in_kb as size,
    case when installs_clean<100000 then 0
    else 1 end as popular_or_not
  FROM
    `team-7-ba770.googleplayapps.total_distinct`, params
  WHERE
     MOD(ABS(FARM_FINGERPRINT(app)),2) = params.EVAL
  )

  SELECT *
  FROM appinfo
  ))
